snippet.textDisplay:
This is a horrifying epidemic.  At the same time, Johns Hopkins admitted in a 2016 study that 250,000 people die every year because of medical error.  That does not include non-error adverse prescription drug reactions, which could well add another 100,000 to that figure.  These figures have done nothing but increase over the past ten years.

Medical error alone killed 2,500,000 Americans over the past ten years.  This includes everything from wrong side surgery to hospital infections.

Why is medical error such a media hot potato?  Further, the medical industry itself should have known that it was woefully unprepared for a large-scale epidemic?

I am no a supporter of this president, but at the same time am left aghast that we as citizens - and the main stream media - are clueless about the true social costs of medical error and adverse drug reactions.

This is a medical train wreck, brought on by inept leadership and an industry that truly should have seen it coming.
